%I A393591 #17 Mar 05 2026 19:43:35
%S A393591 2,3,2,3,3,2,2,3,2,2,2,2,2,5,2,3,3,2,2,3,2,3,3,3,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,3,3,3,
%T A393591 3,2,2,5,2,3,3,4,4,3,2,2,2,3,3,3,4,3,3,2,2,4,2,2,2,2,2,4,2,3,3,3,3,3,
%U A393591 3,3,3,3,3,3,4,3,3,3,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,2,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,3,3,3,2,3,3,2,2,3,4
%N A393591 Greatest integer b such that the sum of the integer digits of n in bases 2..b strictly increases.
%C A393591 Even if we interpret A000042 as base 1, it cannot be incorporated into this sequence, since the count of ones in A000042 would always exceed the count of ones in base 2.
%H A393591 Robert Israel, <a href="/A393591/b393591.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A393591 For the examples, define f(n, b) as the sum of the digits in the representation of n in base b.
%e A393591 a(1) is 2 because f(1, 3) is not larger than f(1, 2);
%e A393591 a(2) is 3 because f(2, 2) is less than f(2, 3) but f(2, 3) is not less than f(2, 4);
%e A393591 a(14) is 5 because f(14, 2) < f(14, 3) < f(14, 4) < f(14, 5) but f(14, 5) is not less than f(14, 6), etc.
%p A393591 f:= proc(n) local b,s,sb;
%p A393591   s:= convert(convert(n,base,2),`+`);
%p A393591   for b from 3 do
%p A393591     sb:= convert(convert(n,base,b),`+`);
%p A393591     if sb <= s then return b-1 fi;
%p A393591     s:= sb
%p A393591   od;
%p A393591 end proc:
%p A393591 map(f, [$1..200]); # _Robert Israel_, Feb 22 2026
%t A393591 a[n_] := Block[{b = 3, c = Total[ IntegerDigits[n, 2]]}, While[d = Total[ IntegerDigits[n, b]]; c < d, c = d; b++]; b - 1]; Array[a, 105]
%o A393591 (PARI) isok(n, b)= my(v=vector(b-1, bb, sumdigits(n, bb+1))); v == Set(v);
%o A393591 a(n) = my(b=2); while (isok(n,b), b++); b-1; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Feb 27 2026
%Y A393591 Cf. A393592.
%K A393591 base,nonn,new
%O A393591 1,1
%A A393591 _Robert G. Wilson v_, Feb 22 2026
